    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110031\">Patrick Massot</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/287929-mathlib4/topic/simp.3F.20giving.20nonsense.20lemmas/near/403179109\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It would be nice to use the opportunity to work on getting <code>simp?</code> closer to optionally output a <code>simp_rw</code>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is where I make my obligatory reference to <a href=\"https://github.com/nomeata/lean-calcify/\"><code>calcify</code></a>, which produces <code>calc</code> proof, but could arguably also produce a sequence of <code>simp_rw</code> steps. The main difference is that it doesn’t work by <code>simp</code> keeping track of what it does , but rather looking at the resulting proof term and determine what really has been done by <code>simp</code>, so maybe easier and more orthogonal to implement… </p>\n<p>although it will fall over in the presence of simpprocs, so hmm, nevermind.</p>",
